Change-Id: I1082858ed78d9b2e4738ce30b231955973d49e1e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/aws-tensorflow-bot/tensorflow/commits/4305d81290a50330ae35b7cf69431c8a2128421f"},{"sha":"93d2356b460c658e6eaf7c84e9d4a679cd05c266","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Remove `OP_REQUIRES` call from helper function.

Since `OP_REQUIRES` macro expands to a `return;` (among other), calling it in a helper function only ends the helper function's execution earlier, but the kernel will still run from start to end. Change-Id: I1082858ed78d9b2e4738ce30b231955973d49e1e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/aws-tensorflow-bot/tensorflow/commits/2fdcef989a366d5dbb78e763af597dd954dcbcd5"},{"sha":"54f3e395ba891f6535e71440fba722568db17d98","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Remove `OP_REQUIRES` call from helper function.

Since `OP_REQUIRES` macro expands to a `return;` (among other), calling it in a helper function only ends the helper function's execution earlier, but the kernel will still run from start to end. Thus, all the expected validations are actually broken/useless as the code ploughs through the next crash anyway.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 375180498
Change-Id: Ie9c2172a1fba6712690b12a9e2b43b761a2e33b5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/7a681d3efb9781862d866f2f3d81e573e7d4ad82"},{"sha":"e2f1b934b554c718bca5a96d1b944850bc8830aa","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Get rid of explicit D2H copies in GPU NMS implementation.

Instead, have the GPU write directly to pinned CPU memory.

The GPU can do only one D2H memcopy at once.  If there is already a D2H memcopy
running, we have to wait until it's complete before we can do the one here.

But if we write directly to pinned memory, we don't have this problem.

We've observed this technique elsewhere lead to large latency reductions in
contended cases.

Change-Id: I408f312e4d49049d2f13a2277300371801172cfd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/fe72d9b50c1fd4990bbb74b8463198511ec658f4"},{"sha":"aa6d441cacf140b929045a13efc5f43840829616","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Fixed wrong side-effect handling for tf.GeneratorDataset op

The special handling of tf.GeneratorDataset in side-effect analysis violated
assumptions for indirectly tracked dependencies, leading to missing control
dependencies even for other unrelated ops surrounding a tf.GeneratorDataset op
(checked by a new test). This change removes the special handling, now
tf.GeneratorDataset is handled as any other non-value-based side-effect.

Instead, have the GPU write directly to pinned CPU memory.

contended cases.

(checked by a new test). This change removes the special handling, now
tf.GeneratorDataset is handled as any other non-value-based side-effect.

Change-Id: I408f312e4d49049d2f13a2277300371801172cfd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/fe72d9b50c1fd4990bbb74b8463198511ec658f4"},{"sha":"aa6d441cacf140b929045a13efc5f43840829616","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Fixed wrong side-effect handling for tf.GeneratorDataset op

The special handling of tf.GeneratorDataset in side-effect analysis violated
assumptions for indirectly tracked dependencies, leading to missing control
dependencies even for other unrelated ops surrounding a tf.GeneratorDataset op
(checked by a new test). This change removes the special handling, now
tf.GeneratorDataset is handled as any other non-value-based side-effect.

Change-Id: If59114fa6bf05545f0033a69930dcb66c1114711","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/guyuchao3/tensorflow/commits/6d8a184710164c7bcc41d3bd29fe4ef46836b6c9"},{"sha":"6b924bda162118c434efd56d8216b73f10dac11c","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Fix unhandled unknown resources in side-effect analysis

1) Previously, function `GetResourceIdsByValue` filtered out all values that are
   not a `ResourceType` (resource variables), even when they have side-effects.
   Such values were wrongly handled as "known resources" which led to missing
   control dependencies in `BreakUpIsland` pass.
2) Added a test catching this case.
3) Added a test for a common sequence of ops using the `DatasetIterator`
   resource which was not tested before.
4) Improved naming for better readability (the term `resource` is overloaded
   with different meanings).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 375180498
Change-Id: Ie9c2172a1fba6712690b12a9e2b43b761a2e33b5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/guyuchao3/tensorflow/commits/7a681d3efb9781862d866f2f3d81e573e7d4ad82"},{"sha":"e2f1b934b554c718bca5a96d1b944850bc8830aa","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Get rid of explicit D2H copies in GPU NMS implementation.

Instead, have the GPU write directly to pinned CPU memory.

The GPU can do only one D2H memcopy at once.  If there is already a D2H memcopy
running, we have to wait until it's complete before we can do the one here.

But if we write directly to pinned memory, we don't have this problem.

We've observed this technique elsewhere lead to large latency reductions in
contended cases.

1) Previously, function `GetResourceIdsByValue` filtered out all values that are
   not a `ResourceType` (resource variables), even when they have side-effects.
   Such values were wrongly handled as "known resources" which led to missing
   control dependencies in `BreakUpIsland` pass.
2) Added a test catching this case.
3) Added a test for a common sequence of ops using the `DatasetIterator`
   resource which was not tested before.
4) Improved naming for better readability (the term `resource` is overloaded
   with different meanings).

Change-Id: Ie9c2172a1fba6712690b12a9e2b43b761a2e33b5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/7a681d3efb9781862d866f2f3d81e573e7d4ad82"},{"sha":"e2f1b934b554c718bca5a96d1b944850bc8830aa","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Get rid of explicit D2H copies in GPU NMS implementation.

Instead, have the GPU write directly to pinned CPU memory.

The GPU can do only one D2H memcopy at once.  If there is already a D2H memcopy
running, we have to wait until it's complete before we can do the one here.

But if we write directly to pinned memory, we don't have this problem.

We've observed this technique elsewhere lead to large latency reductions in
contended cases.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 375180498
Change-Id: Ie9c2172a1fba6712690b12a9e2b43b761a2e33b5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/7a681d3efb9781862d866f2f3d81e573e7d4ad82"},{"sha":"e2f1b934b554c718bca5a96d1b944850bc8830aa","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Get rid of explicit D2H copies in GPU NMS implementation.

Instead, have the GPU write directly to pinned CPU memory.

The GPU can do only one D2H memcopy at once.  If there is already a D2H memcopy
running, we have to wait until it's complete before we can do the one here.

But if we write directly to pinned memory, we don't have this problem.

We've observed this technique elsewhere lead to large latency reductions in
contended cases.

[{"sha":"aa6d441cacf140b929045a13efc5f43840829616","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Fixed wrong side-effect handling for tf.GeneratorDataset op

The special handling of tf.GeneratorDataset in side-effect analysis violated
assumptions for indirectly tracked dependencies, leading to missing control
dependencies even for other unrelated ops surrounding a tf.GeneratorDataset op
(checked by a new test). This change removes the special handling, now
tf.GeneratorDataset is handled as any other non-value-based side-effect.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 375180498
Change-Id: Ie9c2172a1fba6712690b12a9e2b43b761a2e33b5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/7a681d3efb9781862d866f2f3d81e573e7d4ad82"},{"sha":"e2f1b934b554c718bca5a96d1b944850bc8830aa","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Get rid of explicit D2H copies in GPU NMS implementation.

Instead, have the GPU write directly to pinned CPU memory.

The GPU can do only one D2H memcopy at once.  If there is already a D2H memcopy
running, we have to wait until it's complete before we can do the one here.

But if we write directly to pinned memory, we don't have this problem.

We've observed this technique elsewhere lead to large latency reductions in
contended cases.

The connection block schema defines the bastion_port argument as a
number, but we were incorrectly trying to convert it from a string. This
commit fixes that by attempting to convert the cty.Number to the int
result type, returning the error on failure.

An alternative approach would be to change the bastion_port argument in
the schema to be a string, matching the port argument. I'm less sure
about the secondary effects of that change, though.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kanishk98/terraform/commits/0cbe4d8efb9284f714f69b46dd9263bb3ee621b6"},{"sha":"0f936b9d80c29d653811e8a15265911bdbd9c902","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"plans/planfile: Read state snapshots as part of reading a plan

Our model for plans/planfile has unfortunately grown inconsistent with
changes to our modeling of plans.Plan.

Originally we considered the plan "header" and the planned changes as an
entirely separate artifact from the prior state, but we later realized
that carrying the prior state around with the plan is important to
ensuring we always have enough context to faithfully render a plan to the
user, and so we added the prior state as a field of plans.Plan.
More recently we've also added the "previous run state" to plans.Plan for
similar reasons.

Unfortunately as a result of that modeling drift our ReadPlan method was
silently producing an incomplete plans.Plan object, causing use-cases like
"terraform show" to produce slightly different results due to the
plan object not round-tripping completely.

As a short-term tactical fix, here we add state snapshot reading into the
ReadPlan function. This is not an ideal solution because it means that
in the case of applying a plan, where we really do need access to the
state _file_, we'll end up reading the prior state file twice. However,
the goal here is only to heal the modelling quirk with as little change
as possible, because we're not currently at a point where we'd be willing
to risk regressions from a larger refactoring.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kanishk98/terraform/commits/0f936b9d80c29d653811e8a15265911bdbd9c902"},{"sha":"0ee76b92b8ae35d5d0528d024bd338983b543593","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Update working state for resource instances in refresh-only mode

Previously in refresh-only mode we were skipping making any updates to the
working state at all. That's not correct, though: if the state upgrade or
refresh steps detected changes then we need to at least commit _those_ to
the working state, because those can then be detected by downstream
objects like output values.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kanishk98/terraform/commits/0ee76b92b8ae35d5d0528d024bd338983b543593"},{"sha":"b38f3301d1d8fbe1550758449fddfe3ee5d9fe65","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/views: Remove baseState argument from plan-rendering views

This pattern follows as a natural consequence of how for_each is defined,
but I've noticed from community forum Q&A that newcomers often don't
immediately notice the connection between what for_each expects as input
and what a for_each resource produces as a result, so my aim here is to
show a short example of that in the hope of helping folks see the link
here and get ideas on how to employ the technique in other situations.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kanishk98/terraform/commits/6f680653265d2eca84a768e7fd2bd60148daf46b"},{"sha":"bf396b5f1b89536725a3be35d7500a17cb1045b3","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/views: main View type aware if it's running in automation

This "running in automation" idea is a best effort thing where we try to
avoid printing out specific suggestions of commands to run in the main
workflow when the user is running Terraform inside a wrapper script or
other automation, because they probably don't want to bypass that
automation.

This just makes that information available to the main views.View type,
so we can then make use of it in the implementation of more specialized
view types that embed views.View.

However, nothing is using it as of this commit. We'll use it in later
commits.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kanishk98/terraform/commits/bf396b5f1b89536725a3be35d7500a17cb1045b3"},{"sha":"b402fd9d3ab0fc79244a5df178564579d7f72c1a","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/views: Remove command-specific runningInAutomation

We now have RunningInAutomation has a general concern in views.View, so
we no longer need to specify it for each command-specific constructor
separately.

For this initial change I focused only on changing the exported interface
of the views package and let the command-specific views go on having their
own unexported fields containing a copy of the flag because it made this
change less invasive and I wasn't feeling sure yet about whether we
ought to have code within command-specific views directly access the
internals of views.View. However, maybe we'll simplify this further in
a later commit if we conclude that these copies of the flag are
burdensome.

The general version of this gets set directly inside the main package,
which might at some future point allow us to make the command package
itself unaware of this "running in automation" idea and thus reinforce
that it's intended as a presentation-only thing rather than as a
behavioral thing, but we'll save more invasive refactoring for another
day.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kanishk98/terraform/commits/b402fd9d3ab0fc79244a5df178564579d7f72c1a"},{"sha":"fa676bde7c049d573534a04958efb778f53e0414","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"core: Use number for port in connection schema

  technically more correct and consistent with `bastion_port`;
- Use `uint16` as the struct member type for both ports instead of
